<subSubSection id="E6AC8EDE1266FFD8FF77FE60C08BBBED" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="AE09DD551266FFD8FF77FE60C08BBBED" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis id="9CC201471266FFD8FF77FE60C13BBB91" bold="true" box="[199,334,403,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is taken from the Caspian Hyrcanian mixed forest in the southern part of Caspian Sea.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E6AC8EDE1266FFD8FF77FE29C415BE65" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="AE09DD551266FFD8FF77FE29C0A4B999" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis id="9CC201471266FFD8FF77FE29C13ABBC8" bold="true" box="[199,335,474,500]" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">Comments.</emphasis>
In the key to species of 
<taxonomicName id="69B6A6D61266FFD8FDECFE28C2A7BBC9" authorityName="Ratzeburg" authorityYear="1852" box="[604,722,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Coccobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9CC201471266FFD8FDECFE28C2A7BBC9" box="[604,722,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">Coccobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
given by 
<bibRefCitation id="CA27A0A41266FFD8FC8FFE28C3A0BBC9" author="Hayat, M." box="[831,981,474,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" pagination="289 - 334" refId="ref2823" refString="Hayat, M. (1985) Notes on some species of Coccobius and Prophyscus (Hymenoptera: Aphelinidae), with special reference to Girault and Howard types. Oriental Insects, 18, 289 - 334. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00305316.1984.10432208" type="journal article" year="1985">Hayat (1985)</bibRefCitation>
, this new species runs to couplet number 11, but differs from 
<taxonomicName id="69B6A6D61266FFD8FECDFE0CC35FB825" authority="(Yasnosh &amp; Myartseva)" baseAuthorityName="Yasnosh &amp; Myartseva" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[381,810,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Coccobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indefinitus">
<emphasis id="9CC201471266FFD8FECDFE0CC260B825" box="[381,533,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">C. indefinitus</emphasis>
(Yasnosh &amp; Myartseva)
</taxonomicName>
mainly in the following characters: gaster dark brown, with TVII pale brown; antenna with F1 shorter than pedicel, and 1.3× as long as broad; F3 longer than F1 and F2 individually; mid lobe of mesoscutum with fine, largely elongate reticulate sculpture, and scutellum with sculpture similar to that of the mid lobe; mid lobe of mesoscutum with at least 20 setae; fore wing about 3× (2.89×–3.11×) as long as broad, with marginal fringe at least one-third wing width; ovipositor, as seen through the derm, extends from TII of gaster. (In 
<emphasis id="9CC201471266FFD8FE23FD40C246B8F1" box="[403,563,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">
<taxonomicName id="69B6A6D61266FFD8FE23FD40C259B8F1" baseAuthorityName="Yasnosh &amp; Myartseva" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[403,556,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Coccobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indefinitus">C. indefinitus</taxonomicName>
:
</emphasis>
gaster pale yellow, with lateral brown bands on tergites TI–TVI; antenna with F1 subequal in length to pedicel, and about 1.5× as long as broad and longer than F3; mid lobe of mesoscutum with elongate reticulate sculpture, nearly quadratic in the middle; only 4 setae are shown in fig. 1.III by the authors; fore wing clearly less than 3× as long as broad, with marginal fringe very short; ovipositor extends from TIV of gaster. Characters of this species were noted from the original description and the figures. The authors did not mention the number of setae on the mid lobe of mesoscutum, and the relative lengths of the ovipositor, third valvula and mid tibia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AE09DD551266FFD8FF77FC5CC415BE65" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">
This new species appears more similar to 
<taxonomicName id="69B6A6D61266FFD8FD10FC5CC3E2B9F6" authority="(Risbec)" baseAuthorityName="Risbec" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[672,919,943,970]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Coccobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cussoniae">
<emphasis id="9CC201471266FFD8FD10FC5CC35AB9F4" box="[672,815,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">C. cussoniae</emphasis>
(Risbec)
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="CA27A0A41266FFD8FC62FC5CC40CB9F5" author="Prinsloo, G. L." box="[978,1145,942,969]" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" pagination="1517 - 1541" refId="ref3082" refString="Prinsloo, G. L. (1995) Revision of the southern African species of Coccobius Ratzeburg (Hymenoptera: Aphelinidae), parasitoids of armoured scale insects (Homoptera: Diaspididae). Journal of Natural History, 29, 1517 - 1541. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222939500770651" type="journal article" year="1995">Prinsloo, 1995</bibRefCitation>
), especially in the dimensions of the fore wing and longer marginal fringe; in the sculpture of the scutellum; and in the relative lengths of the ovipositor stylets and mid tibia. But 
<taxonomicName id="69B6A6D61266FFD8FDE5FC04C291BE2C" baseAuthorityName="Risbec" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[597,740,1015,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Coccobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cussoniae">
<emphasis id="9CC201471266FFD8FDE5FC04C291BE2C" box="[597,740,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="591">C. cussoniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the new species in the following characters: body colour entirely yellow brown; legs completely pale; antennal pedicel subequal in length to F1; F1–F3 subequal in length, each segment 1.7× as long as broad; and in having the postmarginal vein short.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
